<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-09-19T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-09-19T19:00:00-05:00" n="285" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d285">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">835.00/9–1545: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Ambassador in Argentina</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Braden</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-09-19T20:00:00-04:00">September
                                    19, 1945—8 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1302. Following from Secretary in London: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“Delsec 30, Sept 18.<note n="23" xml:id="d285fn23">Not
                                        printed.</note> Advise Braden Council instructed by heads of
                                    govts to consider certain matters mentioned in protocol.<note n="24" xml:id="d285fn24">For text, see <ref target="frus1945Berlinv02#pg_1477">
                                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, The Conference
                                            of Berlin (The Potsdam Conference), 1945, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, pp. 1477</ref> ff.</note>
                                    Argentine problems not being included, will not be considered by
                                    council. I do expect to discuss general subject with
                                        Bevin.”<note n="25" xml:id="d285fn25">Ernest Bevin, British
                                        Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs.</note>
                                </p>
                            </quote>
                        </p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>